		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message29307401">I really enjoyed re-reading Hotarubi no mori e because all of the stories felt new to me.  This is in large part because when I look back on it, I don't remember the details of the manga so much as the feelings that it evoked.  It's more about the experience than what's printed on the page.<br />
<br />
Looking back, one thing that I didn't notice the first time I read it is how remarkably simple many of the illustrations are.  There isn't an intense level of attention to detail.  And I think that ultimately, the minimalism of the illustration works in service of the stories being told.  There is something wonderfully "abstract" about something that doesn't fill in all of the details.  Your brain fills in the gaps wherever they exist without being too distracting, and often what your brain fills in is the "best version" of what the artist is trying to achieve.  (This phenomenon is somewhat similar to cases in video production where increased resolution or framerate can make things look "worse.")<br />
<br />
Whenever I read Yuki Midorikawa's manga, I always read slowly.  Part of it is that her stories feel very "ambient" and serene.  There's not a huge amount of tension driving me to see what happens next; I'm more content just to appreciate and revel in whatever page is in front of me.  And that's great, because so much of the story is told through pictures.  Of all the stories in Hotarubi no mori, the second piece (the one with the youkai, that got adapted into an anime) epitomizes this best, and it's my favorite of the bunch.  I definitely get the same vibes from that story that I did from Natsume Yuujinchou, which I love dearly.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
